# mycv — NestJS Backend Standards

## Project Structure

- Feature modules live under `src/<feature>/` with `*.module.ts`, `*.controller.ts`, `*.service.ts`, `*.entity.ts`.
- Shared cross-cutting code: `src/guards/`, `src/interceptors/`, `src/<feature>/dtos/`, `src/<feature>/decorators/`.
- Register entities via `TypeOrmModule.forFeature([Entity])` inside the feature module.

## Controllers & DTOs

- Validate request bodies with DTO classes using `class-validator` decorators (`@IsEmail()`, `@IsString()`, etc.).
- Never return entities directly without serialization — use `@Serialize(DtoClass)` on the controller.
- Response DTOs use `@Expose()` on each field; `SerializeInterceptor` strips everything else.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
@Controller('users')
@Serialize(UserDto)
export class UsersController {
  @Patch(':id')
  updateUser(@Param('id', ParseIntPipe) id: number, @Body() body: UpdateUserDto) {
    return this.usersService.update(id, body);
  }
}
```

## Auth & Guards

- Session auth via `cookie-session`; store `userId` in session on sign-in/sign-up.
- Protect routes with `@UseGuards(AuthGuard)`; ownership checks with `UserOwnerGuard`.
- Access the logged-in user via `@CurrentUser()` decorator (set by `CurrentUserInterceptor`).

## Services & Errors

- Business logic belongs in services, not controllers.
- Throw NestJS HTTP exceptions (`BadRequestException`, `NotFoundException`, `UnauthorizedException`, `ForbiddenException`) — never return error objects manually.
- Use `ParseIntPipe` for route params that must be numbers.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
if (!user) return { error: 'not found' };

// ✅ GOOD
if (!user) throw new NotFoundException('user not found');
```

## TypeORM Entities

- One entity per file, named `*.entity.ts`, exported as a class with `@Entity()`.
- Keep lifecycle hooks (`@AfterInsert`, etc.) minimal — avoid heavy logic in entities.

## Testing

- Unit tests: `*.spec.ts` colocated with source; use `Test.createTestingModule` with mocked dependencies (`useValue`).
- E2E tests live in `test/` with `jest-e2e.json` config.

## Code Style

- Prettier: single quotes, trailing commas.
- Match existing import style and NestJS decorators order (imports → class decorator → method decorators).
- Minimize scope — only change what the task requires; no unrelated refactors.
